---
import Article from "../../../layouts/Article.astro";
import KeyTakeaway from "../../../components/KeyTakeaway.astro";
import InfoBox from "../../../components/InfoBox.astro";
---

<Article
  title="Wyrmspan Cave Strategy: How to Build an Efficient Dragon Engine"
  description="Maximize your cave layout and chain dragon abilities for big combos."
  game="wyrmspan"
  gameTitle="Wyrmspan"
  category="Strategy"
  product="wyrmspan-resource-tokens"
  publishDate="2025-05-06"
>
  <p>
    Wyrmspan's cave system is where the game's strategic depth lives. Unlike
    Wingspan's three simple habitat rows, your cave is a multi-layered space
    that you progressively explore and fill with dragons.
  </p>

  <KeyTakeaway answer="Explore deep early to unlock high-value spots, then fill caves with dragons that chain together. Don't spread too thin across all three cave types." />

  <h2>The Three Cave Types</h2>

  <div class="my-6 grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
    <div class="p-5 bg-red-50 rounded-xl border border-red-200">
      <div class="text-2xl mb-2">🔥</div>
      <h4 class="font-heading font-semibold text-sm text-red-800 mb-1">Crimson Cavern</h4>
      <p class="text-xs text-red-700/70">Resource generation. Dragons here produce gold, meat, or crystals when activated. Your economic engine.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-5 bg-amber-50 rounded-xl border border-amber-200">
      <div class="text-2xl mb-2">💎</div>
      <h4 class="font-heading font-semibold text-sm text-amber-800 mb-1">Golden Grotto</h4>
      <p class="text-xs text-amber-700/70">Card advantage. Draw dragon cards, peek at the deck, or tuck cards for points. Your information engine.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-5 bg-purple-50 rounded-xl border border-purple-200">
      <div class="text-2xl mb-2">🌙</div>
      <h4 class="font-heading font-semibold text-sm text-purple-800 mb-1">Amethyst Abyss</h4>
      <p class="text-xs text-purple-700/70">Egg-laying and scoring. Dragons here multiply your egg production and end-game points. Your score engine.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Core Strategic Principles</h2>

  <div class="my-6 space-y-4">
    <div class="p-5 bg-white rounded-xl border border-bark/10">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
        <span class="text-xl">🎯</span>
        <h3 class="font-heading font-bold text-bark">Specialize, Don't Generalize</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-bark/60">
        Having 2 strong caves beats having 3 mediocre ones. Each dragon you play in a cave
        makes every future activation of that cave stronger (you trigger all dragons in the row).
        Depth beats breadth.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="p-5 bg-white rounded-xl border border-bark/10">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
        <span class="text-xl">⛏️</span>
        <h3 class="font-heading font-bold text-bark">Explore Early, Score Late</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-bark/60">
        The deeper cave slots have stronger bonuses and more space. Spend your early turns
        exploring to unlock the best positions, then fill them with your highest-value
        dragons in later rounds.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="p-5 bg-white rounded-xl border border-bark/10">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
        <span class="text-xl">🔗</span>
        <h3 class="font-heading font-bold text-bark">Chain Dragon Powers</h3>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-bark/60">
        Look for dragons whose abilities feed into each other. A dragon that generates gold +
        a dragon that converts gold into points in the same cave = compounding value every time
        you activate that cave row.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <InfoBox type="tip" title="The Coin Economy">
    Coins are the most flexible resource — they can substitute for almost anything. Early-game dragons that generate coins give you options that pure resource generators don't. Prioritize coin-generating dragons in your first 2–3 plays.
  </InfoBox>

  <h2>Common Mistakes</h2>

  <div class="my-6 space-y-3">
    <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
      <span class="text-lg shrink-0">❌</span>
      <div>
        <h4 class="font-heading font-semibold text-sm text-red-800">Playing expensive dragons too early</h4>
        <p class="text-sm text-red-700/70 mt-1">Big dragons are tempting but cost resources you need for exploration. Cheap dragons early, expensive dragons late.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
      <span class="text-lg shrink-0">❌</span>
      <div>
        <h4 class="font-heading font-semibold text-sm text-red-800">Ignoring exploration bonuses</h4>
        <p class="text-sm text-red-700/70 mt-1">The bonuses you get from exploring are free resources and points. Skipping exploration to play dragons is usually wrong in the first half of the game.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
      <span class="text-lg shrink-0">❌</span>
      <div>
        <h4 class="font-heading font-semibold text-sm text-red-800">Hoarding resources</h4>
        <p class="text-sm text-red-700/70 mt-1">Unlike Wingspan where you can sit on food, Wyrmspan rewards spending. Unspent resources at game end are worth very little.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <InfoBox type="info">
    If you're coming from Wingspan, expect your first game of Wyrmspan to feel slower. By game 3, the systems click and it flows faster than Wingspan for most players.
  </InfoBox>
</Article>
